<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="126" name="Aldehydes, Ketones and Carboxylic Acids">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Compounds containing the carbonyl group (&gt;C=O) are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbonyl compounds</option><option id="B">Alcohols</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Includes aldehydes, ketones, carboxylic acids, etc.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In aldehydes, the carbonyl group is bonded to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrogen and an alkyl/aryl group</option><option id="B">Two alkyl groups</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>General formula R-CHO.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In ketones, the carbonyl group is bonded to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Two alkyl or aryl groups</option><option id="B">One hydrogen</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>General formula R-CO-R'.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carbonyl compounds in which carbonyl carbon is bonded to -OH are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carboxylic acids</option><option id="B">Esters</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>General formula R-COOH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name for Methanal is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Formaldehyde</option><option id="B">Acetaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Simplest aldehyde.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name for Ethanal is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetaldehyde</option><option id="B">Formaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Second member of aldehyde series.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name for Propanone is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetone</option><option id="B">Acetaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Simplest ketone.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>IUPAC name of Benzene carbaldehyde is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzaldehyde</option><option id="B">Benzyl alcohol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also known as Bitter almond oil.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The carbon atom of carbonyl group is ____ hybridized.</text>
            <option id="A">sp2</option><option id="B">sp3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Trigonal planar geometry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carbonyl group is ____ in nature due to electronegativity difference.</text>
            <option id="A">Polar</option><option id="B">Non-polar</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Carbon is partial positive, Oxygen is partial negative.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rosenmund reduction is used to prepare aldehydes from ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acyl chlorides (Acid chlorides)</option><option id="B">Alcohols</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses H2/Pd-BaSO4 (poisoned catalyst).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Stephen reaction converts Nitriles to Aldehydes using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">SnCl2 + HCl followed by hydrolysis</option><option id="B">LiAlH4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Via imine intermediate.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Etard reaction prepares Benzaldehyde from Toluene using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chromyl chloride (CrO2Cl2)</option><option id="B">KMnO4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific reagent for mild oxidation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gattermann-Koch reaction prepares Benzaldehyde from Benzene using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CO + HCl in presence of AlCl3</option><option id="B">Cl2/UV</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formylation of aromatic ring.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Preparation of ketones from Nitriles involves reaction with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Grignard reagent</option><option id="B">H2/Ni</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Followed by hydrolysis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Boiling points of carbonyl compounds are ____ than hydrocarbons of same mass.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher</option><option id="B">Lower</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to dipole-dipole interactions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Boiling points of aldehydes/ketones are ____ than alcohols of same mass.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower</option><option id="B">Higher</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lack of intermolecular hydrogen bonding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of carbonyl compounds in water ____ with increase in chain length.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lower members are soluble due to H-bonding with water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Characteristic reaction for aldehydes and ketones is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nucleophilic addition</option><option id="B">Nucleophilic substitution</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Attack on electron-deficient carbonyl carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aldehydes are generally ____ reactive than ketones in nucleophilic addition.</text>
            <option id="A">More</option><option id="B">Less</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to lower steric hindrance and better electronic factors.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cyanohydrin formation involves addition of ____ to carbonyl compounds.</text>
            <option id="A">HCN</option><option id="B">NH3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Catalyzed by base (to generate CN-).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sodium hydrogensulphite (NaHSO3) addition is used for ____ of carbonyl compounds.</text>
            <option id="A">Purification and separation</option><option id="B">Reduction</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>White crystalline adduct can be hydrolyzed back.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Addition of one molecule of alcohol to an aldehyde gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hemiacetal</option><option id="B">Acetal</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains one alkoxy and one hydroxy group on same carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Addition of excess alcohol to aldehydes in presence of HCl gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetals (gem-dialkoxy compounds)</option><option id="B">Hemiacetals</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complete substitution product.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ketones react with ethylene glycol to form ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cyclic ketals</option><option id="B">Acetals</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Five-membered ring structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ammonia and its derivatives add to carbonyl group to form products ending in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">=N-Z (e.g. imine, hydrazone)</option><option id="B">-NH2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Elimination of water follows addition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Clemmensen reduction converts C=O to CH2 using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zn-Hg and Conc. HCl</option><option id="B">NH2NH2 / KOH</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acidic conditions for reduction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Wolff-Kishner reduction converts C=O to CH2 using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">NH2NH2 and KOH/Ethylene glycol</option><option id="B">Zn-Hg/HCl</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basic conditions for reduction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tollen's reagent is an ____ solution of silver nitrate.</text>
            <option id="A">Ammoniacal</option><option id="B">Acidic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forms silver mirror with aldehydes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Fehling's test is used to distinguish aldehydes from ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ketones</option><option id="B">Alcohols</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Red ppt (Cu2O) with aldehydes, no reaction with ketones.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Benzaldehyde reduces Fehling's solution? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">No (Aromatic aldehydes don't react)</option><option id="B">Yes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Important distinction from aliphatic aldehydes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Iodoform reaction is used to detect ____ group.</text>
            <option id="A">Methyl ketone (CH3-CO-)</option><option id="B">Aldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses NaOI (NaOH + I2).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aldehydes/Ketones with alpha-hydrogen undergo ____ condensation.</text>
            <option id="A">Aldol</option><option id="B">Cannizzaro</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using dilute alkali.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aldol condensation product followed by heating gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">alpha,beta-unsaturated carbonyl compound</option><option id="B">Alcohol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dehydration step.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aldehydes with NO alpha-hydrogen undergo ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Cannizzaro</option><option id="B">Aldol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Self oxidation-reduction using conc. alkali.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cannizzaro products for HCHO are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Methanol and Sodium formate</option><option id="B">Acetaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Disproportionation reaction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Standard carboxylic acid group is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">-COOH</option><option id="B">-CHO</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Carbonyl + Hydroxyl.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name for Methanoic acid is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Formic acid</option><option id="B">Acetic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in red ants.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name for Ethanoic acid is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetic acid</option><option id="B">Formic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Main component of vinegar.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carboxylic acids have ____ boiling points than alcohols of similar mass.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher</option><option id="B">Lower</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to more extensive hydrogen bonding (dimer formation).</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Aldehydes/Ketones react with NH2OH to form ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Oximes</option><option id="B">Hydrazones</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>&gt;C=N-OH structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aldehydes/Ketones react with 2,4-DNP to form ____ precipitates.</text>
            <option id="A">Orange-red hydrazones</option><option id="B">White crystals</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used to detect presence of carbonyl group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Benzaldehyde + Benzaldehyde (conc. NaOH) -&gt; Benzyl alcohol + Sodium benzoate. This is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cannizzaro reaction</option><option id="B">Aldol condensation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Aromatic aldehyde with no alpha-H.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is most reactive in nucleophilic addition?</text>
            <option id="A">Formaldehyde (HCHO)</option><option id="B">Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO)</option><option id="C">Acetone (CH3COCH3)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Least sterically hindered and least electronic stability of C+ center.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity of Carboxylic acids: Presence of EWG (like Cl, F) ____ the acidity.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stabilizes the carboxylate ion by inductive effect.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Order of acidity: FCH2COOH vs ClCH2COOH vs BrCH2COOH? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">F &gt; Cl &gt; Br</option><option id="B">Br &gt; Cl &gt; F</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increasing electronegativity of substituent.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>HVZ (Hell-Volhard-Zelinsky) reaction is used for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alpha-halogenation of carboxylic acids</option><option id="B">Decarboxylation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses X2/Red Phosphorus.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Decarboxylation of Sodium salt of carboxylic acid with Sodalime (NaOH + CaO) gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkane with one less carbon</option><option id="B">Aldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard reduction method.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carboxylic acids are ____ acidic than phenols.</text>
            <option id="A">More</option><option id="B">Less</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Carboxylate ion is better stabilized due to two equivalent oxygen resonance structures.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Schiff's base is formed by reaction of carbonyl compound with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary amine (R-NH2)</option><option id="B">Ammonia</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>&gt;C=N-R structure (substituted imine).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Popoff's rule is related to the oxidation of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Unsymmetric ketones</option><option id="B">Aldehydes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Carbonyl group stays with smaller alkyl group during cleavage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following does NOT reduce Tollen's reagent?</text>
            <option id="A">Acetone</option><option id="B">Acetaldehyde</option><option id="C">Glucose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ketones are generally resistant to mild oxidation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Crossed Aldol condensation occurs between ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Two different aldehydes/ketones</option><option id="B">Two molecules of same aldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can yield a mixture of up to 4 products.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Benzoic acid on nitration gives majorly ____ product.</text>
            <option id="A">m-nitrobenzoic acid</option><option id="B">o/p-nitrobenzoic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>-COOH is a deactivating and meta-directing group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction R-COCl + (R')2Cd -&gt; ketone is a method using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dialkylcadmium</option><option id="B">Grignard reagent directly</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cadmium reagents don't react further with ketones.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vapor phase oxidation of Cumene gives Phenol and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetone</option><option id="B">Methanol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Valuable by-product.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity of acetic acid vs chloroacetic acid? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chloroacetic acid is stronger</option><option id="B">Acetic acid is stronger</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>-I effect of chlorine.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity of benzoic acid vs p-nitrobenzoic acid? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-nitrobenzoic acid is stronger</option><option id="B">Benzoic acid is stronger</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>NO2 is EWG.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity of benzoic acid vs p-methoxybenzoic acid? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzoic acid is stronger</option><option id="B">p-methoxybenzoic acid is stronger</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>OCH3 is EDG (+M), destabilizes carboxylate.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Formic acid reduces Tollen's reagent? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (unusual for an acid)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains an aldehyde-like H-CO group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of carboxylic acid with PCl5 gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acid chloride (RCOCl)</option><option id="B">Alkyl chloride</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Substitution of -OH by -Cl.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carboxylic acid + Ammonia (heat) gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amide (RCONH2)</option><option id="B">Amine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Via ammonium carboxylate salt.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Electrolysis of aqueous solution of sodium carboxylate is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kolbe's electrolytic method</option><option id="B">Hoffmann degradation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Yields alkanes/hydrocarbons at anode.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mechanism for nucleophilic addition involves formation of a ____ intermediate.</text>
            <option id="A">Tetrahedral alkoxide ion</option><option id="B">Planar enolate</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>sp2 changed to sp3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ozonolysis of 1-butene gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Propanal and Methanal</option><option id="B">Ethanal</option>
            <answer>A</answer>Cleavage of double bond.</question>
        <question>
            <text>Fehling solution A consists of aqueous ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Copper sulfate</option><option id="B">Sodium hydroxide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fehling B is Rochelle salt in alkali.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tollen's reagent test is also called ____ test.</text>
            <option id="A">Silver mirror</option><option id="B">Fehling's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Appearance of silver coat on test tube walls.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Benedict's solution is similar to Fehling's but uses ____ instead of tartrate.</text>
            <option id="A">Citrate</option><option id="B">Oxalate</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used for sugar detection.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Formaldehyde is used as ____ under the name Formalin.</text>
            <option id="A">40% aqueous solution (disinfectant/preservative)</option><option id="B">Gas</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>For preserving biological specimens.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acetaldehyde is used in the preparation of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetic acid, ethyl acetate, polymers</option><option id="B">Only solvents</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Versatile intermediate.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bakelite is a polymer of phenol and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Formaldehyde</option><option id="B">Acetone</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Thermosetting plastic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Urotropine is formed by reaction of formaldehyde with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ammonia</option><option id="B">Urea</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hexamethylenetetramine (Urinary antiseptic).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aldol product of acetone is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Diacetone alcohol</option><option id="B">Mesityl oxide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Intermediate in synthesis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Paraldehyde is a trimer of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetaldehyde</option><option id="B">Formaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used as a hypnotic/sedative.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Metaldehyde is a tetramer of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetaldehyde</option><option id="B">Formaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used as a solid fuel (meta-tablets).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Formation of cyanohydrin from acetone is an example of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nucleophilic addition</option><option id="B">Electrophilic addition</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic carbonyl reaction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Effect of pH on ammonia derivative addition? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Requires controlled pH (approx 3.5)</option><option id="B">No effect</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acid catalyst needed for protonation, but too much acid protonates the nucleophile.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mechanism for formation of oxime involves ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Addition followed by dehydration</option><option id="B">Substitution</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>General mechanism for RR'C=N-Z compounds.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes the behavior of carboxylic acids in benzene?</text>
            <option id="A">Exist as dimers</option><option id="B">Monomers</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to intermolecular H-bonding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sodium benzoate is used as a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Food preservative</option><option id="B">Fuel</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prevents bacterial growth.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is most reactive towards nucleophilic addition?</text>
            <option id="A">p-nitrobenzaldehyde</option><option id="B">Benzaldehyde</option><option id="C">p-methoxybenzaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>-NO2 is EWG, increases positive charge on carbonyl carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity order: Trichloroacetic vs Dichloroacetic vs Monochloroacetic acid? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Trichloro &gt; Dichloro &gt; Mono</option><option id="B">Mono &gt; Dichloro &gt; Trichloro</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Accumulative -I effect of chlorine atoms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following does NOT show Aldol condensation?</text>
            <option id="A">Trimethylacetaldehyde [Pivalaldehyde]</option><option id="B">Acetaldehyde</option><option id="C">Propanone</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lacks alpha-hydrogen.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of propanal and acetone in dilute NaOH gives ____ crossed aldol products.</text>
            <option id="A">4 (2 self, 2 crossed)</option><option id="B">2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Both have alpha-hydrogens.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aldol condensation involves ____ attack of enolate on carbonyl.</text>
            <option id="A">Nucleophilic</option><option id="B">Electrophilic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basic mechanism step.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which test distinguishes Methanoic and Ethanoic acids?</text>
            <option id="A">Tollen's reagent</option><option id="B">NaHCO3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formic acid gives silver mirror, acetic acid doesn't.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Heating calcium acetate yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetone</option><option id="B">Acetaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C-C bond formation via dry distillation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Heating a mixture of calcium acetate and calcium formate yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetaldehyde (mainly)</option><option id="B">Acetone</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mixed product formation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of Grignard reagent with CO2 followed by H+ yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carboxylic acid</option><option id="B">Alcohol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increase in chain length by one carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydrolysis of Nitriles with alkali finally yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carboxylates (Sodium salt of acid)</option><option id="B">Amides</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acidified to get free acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of RMgX with acyl chloride yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ketone (but may react further to 3° alcohol)</option><option id="B">Aldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hard to control without low temp or specific reagents.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Beckmann rearrangement of oximes yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amides</option><option id="B">Amines</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using PCl5 or H2SO4.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Schotten-Baumann reaction is an ____ substitution.</text>
            <option id="A">Aromatic nucleophilic (Schotten-Baumann is usually Acylation)</option><option id="B">Electrophilic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wait, it's an acylation of alcohols/amines by acid halides in base.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following has highest boiling point?</text>
            <option id="A">Benzoic acid</option><option id="B">Phenol</option><option id="C">Benzaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strong dimerization in carboxylic acids.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction involving R-COOH + N3H -&gt; R-NH2 is ____.</text>
